result.execSummary:
The defendant James Lee Norris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: In the event probation is revoked, Defendant would be entitled to Good Time Credit and Huber Privileges.

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.
No contact with T. Bean unless specifically authorized by supervising agent.

Defendant to complete an Anger Managment Program together with any follow through counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.   Defendant to comply with any other terms or conditions as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

Case called @ 3:34 p.m. Defendant James Lee Norris in court with attorney Katherine Seifert.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Motion by the State to amend the criminal complaint. Parties have filed standard motions in limine. The Court grants the motions in limine filed by the defense with a few caveats which the Court will address. Motion by the State requesting the admission of other acts evidence. Statement by Atty Seifert - does voice an objection to the admission of the prior incident. The Court finds that the prior incident is allowed. The Court addresses the motion to impeach with prior convictions for the DE and also for the witness. Statement by Atty Seifert regarding the State's Motion to Amend the Complaint. The Court will permit the State to amend the criminal complaint adding the charge of Disorderly Conduct. ADA Anderson - believes that the victim may be evading service of the subpoena. The Court makes a statement regarding that issue. ADA Anderson will provide a sealed offer to the Court the day of trial.
